## Merge Sort a Linked List: Why Merge Sort is Preferred Over Quick Sort

Merge sort is preferred over quick sort for sorting linked lists due to its efficient performance and adaptability to linked list data structures.

### Direct Answer
Merge sort is the most suitable algorithm for sorting linked lists because it has a time complexity of O(n log n) and does not require random access, which makes it more efficient than quick sort.

### Why Merge Sort is Better

According to the search results, merge sort's performance on linked lists is due to its ability to divide the list into smaller sublists and then merge them in sorted order. This approach avoids the need for random access, which can be expensive for linked lists (From http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/merge-sort-for-linked-list/).

### Comparison with Quick Sort

Quick sort, on the other hand, requires random access to choose a pivot element, which can lead to poor performance on linked lists. Additionally, quick sort's partitioning step can be expensive for linked lists (According to the search results).

### Example Code
Here is an example of merge sort implemented for a linked list in C++:
```cpp
// Node structure for the linked list
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
};

// Merge function for merge sort
Node* merge(Node* head1, Node* head2) {
    // Create a new node to store the merged result
    Node* dummy = new Node();
    Node* current = dummy;

    while (head1 != NULL && head2 != NULL) {
        if (head1->data <= head2->data) {
            current->next = head1;
            head1 = head1->next;
        } else {
            current->next = head2;
            head2 = head2->next;
        }
        current = current->next;
    }

    // Append the remaining nodes
    if (head1 != NULL) {
        current->next = head1;
    } else {
        current->next = head2;
    }

    return dummy->next;
}

// Merge sort function for linked list
Node* mergeSort(Node* head) {
    // Base case: If the list has one or zero nodes, it is already sorted
    if (head == NULL || head->next == NULL) {
        return head;
    }

    // Find the middle of the list
    Node* mid = findMiddle(head);

    // Split the list into two halves
    Node* midNext = mid->next;
    mid->next = NULL;

    // Recursively sort both halves
    Node* left = mergeSort(head);
    Node* right = mergeSort(midNext);

    // Merge the sorted halves
    return merge(left, right);
}
```
### Conclusion

In conclusion, merge sort is the preferred algorithm for sorting linked lists due to its efficient performance and adaptability to linked list data structures. Its time complexity of O(n log n) makes it more suitable than quick sort, which can be expensive on linked lists.

