## Getting a Directory Listing in C

To get a directory listing in C, you can use various functions depending on your operating system and requirements.

### Cross-Platform Approach

For a cross-platform approach, you can use the `dirent.h` header file, which is part of the POSIX standard. This allows you to write code that works on both Linux and Windows.

```c
#include <dirent.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    DIR *dir;
    struct dirent *ent;

    if ((dir = opendir(".")) != NULL) {
        while ((ent = readdir(dir)) != NULL) {
            printf("%s\n", ent->d_name);
        }
        closedir(dir);
    } else {
        perror("opendir");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code opens the current directory, reads its contents, and prints each file name.

### Windows-Specific Approach

On Windows, you can use the `FindFirstFile` function from the `windows.h` header file to achieve similar results.

```c
#include <windows.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    WIN32_FIND_DATA ffd;
    HANDLE hFind;

    if ((hFind = FindFirstFile("*", &ffd)) != INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE) {
        do {
            printf("%s\n", ffd.cFileName);
        } while (FindNextFile(hFind, &ffd) != 0);

        FindClose(hFind);
    } else {
        perror("FindFirstFile");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code uses the `FindFirstFile` function to find all files in the current directory and prints their names.

